      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "79f9035f0eb66bd4",
      "text": "In retrospect, it is hard to believe that [[Yurii Andrukhovych]] actually wrote this text in 1992. \"Moscoviada\", published in Ukraine in 1993 and in German in 2006 in the translation by Sabine Stöhr, reads, viewed from today, like the anticipation of a horror scenario that has now occurred. [https://www.republik.ch/2022/03/12/sie-erzaehlen-vom-krieg post]"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "fbef341358f04771",
      "text": "Andrukhovych portrays the Moscow of the very first after-turn days, immediately after the collapse of the Soviet Union. The \"Ukrainian poet Otto von F.,\" in many ways an alter ego of the author, has moved into the associated dormitory for his studies at the Gorky Institute of Literature. Moscow is the Mecca of the post-Soviet intelligentsia, at the same time a place for which the word Moloch could have been invented. And the new promise of freedom associated with the city is, from the very beginning, interspersed with Soviet-nostalgic fantasies of great power, which are already blossoming again more vigorously than the local economy (even vodka is in short supply)."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "7dcb9bacb58289c5",
      "text": "[…] The present is clearly permeated and burdened by history (and its instrumentalizations). Inescapable is the compulsion to locate, with which everyone is immediately sorted into a grid of origin and affiliation. Throughout, the intertwining of national chauvinism and sexism becomes palpable, and it is part of Andrukhovych's narrative consistency that he does not keep his hero free of a chauvinistic mack attitude either. When the budding young poet Otto von F. comments on his own odyssey, he always appears as an unreliable and by no means only sympathetic narrator with whom we sympathize, because he wins us over with his cutting wit and the malicious punch lines of his storytelling."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "2f717a011b8e78e1",
      "text": "[…] The episode about the perfidious psycho-strategies of the KGB is brilliant. And it takes on new topicality against the background of more recent Putin speeches. Otto, in fact, is being blackmailed by Russian agents by threatening to publicly discredit him as the grandson of fascist Ukrainian war criminals. The instrumentalization of accusations of fascism against Ukrainian citizens: Even Andrukhovych would probably not have dreamed that Putin today plays on this keyboard even more unscrupulously and defames even the government of a Jewish president as a \"gang of drug addicts and neo-Nazis\" (which is tantamount to an anti-Semitic perpetrator-victim reversal) without any reference to reality."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "744d7e3c94be3b9b",
      "text": "[…] However, Andrukhovych's novel becomes an almost prophetic text through its final scene.\n\nWhen Otto von F. finally reaches the department store \"Kinderwelt\" and realizes that perhaps \"our children are losing their childhood right here,\" he follows a pickpocket to the department store basement. Not only does a brutal fight ensue there; Otto von F. also gets deeper and deeper into the city's underworld from here. Of all places, the basement of the \"Kinderwelt\" becomes a symbol of the morass, the abysmal nature of the Kremlin city and the bottomless pit of all hopes for freedom.\n\nThrough a cascade of ever new episodes that escalate into the grotesque, typical of this novel, Otto finally ends up in a surreal carnival of grimaces: a kind of party congress as a sinister masked ball.\n\nThe speaker at the front has a black stocking pulled over his head, \"with a slit for the mouth\" (which is why the narrator henceforth calls him Schwarzstrumpf). Audience and presidium, they all resurrect figures of Russian history in their disguises: There's Lenin, Ivan the Terrible, Catherine II, and other figures from the history books: \"a symposium of the dead about our future.\"\n\n\"To be or not to be a great power,\" Blackstocking preaches his motto, announcing the resurrection of the Empire. \"The amputated arms and legs grow together again to form a whole,\" he announces to the cheering audience, the idea of independence will finally suffer a global defeat. One has \"a millennial goal\" and this \"is called subjugation of the world\".\n\nWith Schwarzstrumpf's speech in front of a cabinet of horrors of historical distortion, Andrukhovych had already, at the beginning of the 1990s, put the threat of a Soviet-nostalgic imperialism into the picture, for which the disintegration of the Soviet Union serves only as the driving force of a renewed claim to great power. The final scene of \"Moscoviada\" is a literary farce whose oppressively realistic background is glaringly obvious today. Andrukhovych, one must conclude, has already identified the concrete danger of war by imperialist ideologists in the Moscow of the first post-reunification period. "
    },
