        "text": "[…] However, Andrukhovych's novel becomes an almost prophetic text through its final scene.\n\nWhen Otto von F. finally reaches the department store \"Kinderwelt\" and realizes that perhaps \"our children are losing their childhood right here,\" he follows a pickpocket to the department store basement. Not only does a brutal fight ensue there; Otto von F. also gets deeper and deeper into the city's underworld from here. Of all places, the basement of the \"Kinderwelt\" becomes a symbol of the morass, the abysmal nature of the Kremlin city and the bottomless pit of all hopes for freedom.\n\nThrough a cascade of ever new episodes that escalate into the grotesque, typical of this novel, Otto finally ends up in a surreal carnival of grimaces: a kind of party congress as a sinister masked ball.\n\nThe speaker at the front has a black stocking pulled over his head, \"with a slit for the mouth\" (which is why the narrator henceforth calls him Schwarzstrumpf). Audience and presidium, they all resurrect figures of Russian history in their disguises: There's Lenin, Ivan the Terrible, Catherine II, and other figures from the history books: \"a symposium of the dead about our future.\"\n\n\"To be or not to be a great power,\" Blackstocking preaches his motto, announcing the resurrection of the Empire. \"The amputated arms and legs grow together again to form a whole,\" he announces to the cheering audience, the idea of independence will finally suffer a global defeat. One has \"a millennial goal\" and this \"is called subjugation of the world\".\n\nWith Schwarzstrumpf's speech in front of a cabinet of horrors of historical distortion, Andrukhovych had already, at the beginning of the 1990s, put the threat of a Soviet-nostalgic imperialism into the picture, for which the disintegration of the Soviet Union serves only as the driving force of a renewed claim to great power. The final scene of \"Moscoviada\" is a literary farce whose oppressively realistic background is glaringly obvious today. Andrukhovych, one must conclude, has already identified the concrete danger of war by imperialist ideologists in the Moscow of the first post-reunification period. Translated with www.DeepL.com/Translator (free version)"
